 *1246422696*Painting by weight
 via id:tgbt <a href='http://www.art-meter.com/'>Painted! It connects want.　| ART-Meter: a site for measuring and selling paintings</a>.
 He felt that selling paintings by weight was an oblique idea, so <a href="http://www.amazon.co.jp/gp/product/4048700022?ie=UTF8&tag=nishiohirokaz-22&linkCode=as2&camp=247& creative=7399&creativeASIN=4048700022">Contemporary Art Business</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.jp/e/ir?t=nishiohirokaz-22&l=as2&o=9&a= 4048700022" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border:none !important; margin:0px !important;" />Taken from
 
 >>
 Primary price is determined by size and material/// i.e., all 100 paintings produced by the same artist at the same time are the same price.
 <<
 
 So, the weigh-in itself is not as oblique as it sounds. However, I thought the stance of creating a sense of fairness and value for money by bringing it to the forefront was a pretty good idea.
 
 My work is an acrylic board, so I can't sign it on the front, so I can't sell it here, but let's calculate how much it would cost if it were a CG stand-alone, not wrapped in acrylic. The calculation method is clearly stated: <a href='http://www.art-meter.com/guide/customer/detail/'>Buying Guide</a>. A3 is 1247.40 square centimeters, which is 6,250 yen assuming the lowest unit price. The acrylic processing would increase the cost by a little more than 5 times, so the estimated cost would be 31800 yen.
 
 The painter's level is interesting: if two A3 works are sold, the level rises to 8750 yen; if two more are sold, 11250 yen; if four more are sold, 13750 yen; and if four more are sold, the artist enters the blue ceiling zone. Interesting. I think I'll stop sticking to acrylics and put some of my pieces out here.
 
